","\n","# 1. DATA PREPARATION\n","# Standard: We define our features (house_sizes) and labels (house_price).\n","# Note: In deep learning, unscaled large numbers can cause the gradient to explode, leading to 'NaN' results.\n","# Bhai Style: House ka size aur uska price set kiya. Par yaad rakhna, agar numbers bohot bade honge\n","# toh model ka dimaag chakra jayega (NaN error), isliye real project mein scaling zaroori hai.\n","house_sizes = np.array([0.5, 0.7, 1.0, 1.25, 1.5, 1.75, 2.0], dtype=float) # Sizes in 1000s of sq ft\n","house_price = np.array([100, 150, 200, 250, 300, 350, 400], dtype=float) # Prices in $1000s\n","\n","# 2. MODEL ARCHITECTURE\n","# Standard: A single Dense layer with 1 unit and 1 input shape represents a simple linear regression: y = wx + b.\n","# Bhai Style: Ek simple 'Sequential' model banaya jisme ek hi neuron (Dense) hai.\n","# Yeh bas ye seekh raha hai ki size badhne par price kitna badhta hai.\n","model = tf.keras.Sequential([tf.keras.layers.Dense(units=1, input_shape=[1])])\n","\n","# 3. COMPILATION\n","# Standard: Using SGD optimizer and Mean Squared Error to measure how well the model fits the data.\n","# Bhai Style: Model ki setting kar di. 'sgd' rasta dikhayega aur 'loss' galti batayega.\n","model.compile(optimizer='sgd', loss='mean_squared_error')\n","\n","# 4. TRAINING\n","# Standard: The model iterates 500 times to minimize the loss function.\n","# Bhai Style: .fit matlab 'Riyaz'. 500 baar model is data ko ghol ke piyega taaki prediction sahi ho.\n","model.fit(house_sizes, house_price, epochs=500, verbose=0)\n","\n","# 5. PREDICTION\n","# Standard: Predicting the price for a house of 2250 sq ft (passed as 2.25 to match our scaled data).\n","# Bhai Style: Ab asli test! 2250 sq ft (2.25) ka rate pucha toh model purane pattern se calculate karke batayega.\n","input_val = 2.25\n","predicted_price = model.predict(np.array([input_val]))\n","print(f\"Predicted price for {input_val*1000} sq ft house: ${predicted_price[0][0]*1000:,.2f}\")\n","\n","model.save('house_prediction_model.keras')"],"metadata":{"id":"xgckd9AK3V3l"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["# Normal Terms: This cell demonstrates a very basic linear regression model using TensorFlow/Keras.\n","# It aims to find a simple relationship between input (X) and output (y).\n","# Bhai Language: Apun idhar ek dum simple wala machine learning model bana raha hai. Kya hai na, yeh model X ko dekh ke y ko samajhne ki koshish karega, jaise math mein 'y = mx + c' hota hai na, bas waisa hi kuch. Ek dum fundamental cheez hai boss!\n","\n","# Normal Terms: Import the TensorFlow library, which is a powerful open-source platform for machine learning.\n","# It provides a comprehensive ecosystem of tools, libraries, and community resources.\n","# Bhai Language: Pehle apun TensorFlow ko import karega. Yeh machine learning ka asli 'baap' hai, sab bade-bade kaam yahi karta hai. Iske bina apna ML ka dhandha nahi chalega!\n","import tensorflow as tf\n","\n","# Normal Terms: Import the NumPy library, which is essential for numerical operations in Python.\n","# It provides support for large, multi-dimensional arrays and matrices, along with a collection of mathematical functions to operate on these arrays.\n","# Bhai Language: NumPy bhi bahut zaroori hai. Saara number crunching, arrays banana, calculation karna, yeh sab NumPy ke bina adhoora hai. Apne data ko set karne ke liye iski bahut zaroorat padegi.\n","import numpy as np\n","\n","# Normal Terms: Define a sequential model, which is a linear stack of layers.\n","# `tf.keras.layers.Dense(units=1, input_shape=[1])` creates a single fully connected layer with 1 neuron (unit).\n","# `input_shape=[1]` tells the model that each input will be a single value.\n","# This setup represents a simple linear equation: output = weight * input + bias.\n","# Bhai Language: Ab apun model banayega. `Sequential` matlab seedha-seedha ek ke baad ek layers jodna. Apun ne ek hi 'Dense' layer lagayi hai, jaise ek hi dimag ka cell ho. Ismein 1 'unit' hai matlab ek hi calculation ka point, aur `input_shape=[1]` matlab, ek time pe ek hi number input mein aayega. Samajh le, ek number do, dusra number answer mein milega, seedha hisaab!\n","model = tf.keras.Sequential([tf.keras.layers.Dense(units=1, input_shape=[1])])\n","\n","# Normal Terms: Compile the model, which configures it for training.\n","# `optimizer='sgd'` specifies the optimization algorithm: Stochastic Gradient Descent. It's like the strategy the model uses to learn and adjust its internal parameters (weights and biases) to minimize the loss.\n","# `loss='mean_squared_error'` defines the loss function. This function measures how far the model's predictions are from the actual true values. Mean Squared Error is commonly used for regression problems, penalizing larger errors more significantly.\n","# Bhai Language: Model ko ab 'ready' kar rahe hain training ke liye. `compile` matlab settings set karna.\n","# `optimizer='sgd'` bata raha hai ki model kaise sikhega, kaise apni galtiyaan sudharega. Jaise teacher batata hai na ki aise padho toh exam mein achhe number aayenge, waisa hi kuch.\n","# `loss='mean_squared_error'` matlab, agar model galat guess karega toh kitna bura lagega usko. Yeh ek tarah se 'galti ka meter' hai. Jitni zyada galti, utna zyada 'loss', aur model utna hi zyada try karega uss loss ko kam karne ka.\n","model.compile(optimizer='sgd',loss='mean_squared_error')\n","\n","# Normal Terms: Prepare the training data.\n","# `np.array([...], dtype=float)` creates NumPy arrays of floating-point numbers.\n","# `X` represents the input features (e.g., [1.0, 2.0, 3.0, 4.0]).\n","# `y` represents the corresponding target labels (e.g., [2.0, 4.0, 6.0, 8.0]).\n","# In this simple example, we can observe a clear linear relationship: y = 2 * X.\n","# Bhai Language: Apun ne ab data banaya hai jisse model seekhega.\n","# `X` apna input hai, jo numbers model ko denge. Aur `y` uska sahi jawab hai, jo model ko sikhana hai. Jaise bacche ko sikhate hai na '1+1=2', '2+2=4', waisa hi kuch. Yahan pe toh dikh raha hai ki 'y' hamesha 'X' ka double hai, toh model ko yahi sikhana hai.\n","X =np.array([1.0,2.0,3.0,4.0],dtype=float)\n","y =np.array([2.0,4.0,6.0,8.0],dtype=float)\n","\n","# Normal Terms: Train the model on the prepared data.\n","# `model.fit(X, y, epochs=100, verbose=0)` starts the training process.\n","# `X` is the input data, and `y` is the target data.\n","# `epochs=100` means the model will go through the entire dataset 100 times. Each pass helps the model refine its understanding of the data's patterns.\n","# `verbose=0` suppresses the output during training, meaning it won't print progress updates to the console.\n","# Bhai Language: Ab asli training shuru! `model.fit` matlab model ko 'padhai' karwana. `X` aur `y` uska syllabus hai.\n","# `epochs=100` matlab model 100 baar puri kitaab padhega. Jitni baar padhega, utna hi zyaada samajhdar banega.\n","# `verbose=0` matlab training ke time screen pe kuch dikhayega nahi, chup-chap apna kaam karega background mein. Kyunki show-off nahi karne ka!\n","model.fit(X , y, epochs=100, verbose=0)\n","\n","# Normal Terms: Use the trained model to make a prediction for a new input value.\n","# `model.predict(np.array([10.0]))` asks the model to predict the output for an input of 10.0.\n","# The input is wrapped in `np.array([10.0])` because Keras models expect input in array format, even for a single value.\n","# Bhai Language: Ab time hai model ka test lene ka! `model.predict` matlab model se poochhna ki 'bhaiya, agar 10.0 input doon toh kya jawab doge?'\n","# `np.array([10.0])` mein isliye daala kyunki model bolta hai, 'bhai, akela number nahi, array mein bhejo, tabhi main samajh paunga.' Toh 10.0 ko array mein daal ke bheja hai predict karne ke liye. Dekhte hain kitna sikha hai apna model!\n","model.predict(np.array([10.0]))"],"metadata":{"id":"ZR40ao_w3aGs"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","